CNEOS Close Approach Data Exploration

Cory Cone

2/23/2020

1 Introduction

The Center for Near-Earth Object Studies (CNEOS) is a division of NASA computing ateroid and comit orbits and their odds of Earth Impact. (source: https://cneos.jpl.nasa.gov/)

For this analysis, I used datasets queried from the NEO database that include all NEOs matching a certain criteria (described below) as well as a second dataset of those that have any probability (past, present, future) of an hitting Earth.

I wanted to analyze these datasets not only because the subject matter is exciting, but because this particular data is very new to me, and wanted to see how I did with data and values that were unfamiliar to those I’d worked with in the past (for instance, Lunar Distance and NEO Diameter). I also thought these particular datasets posed some tidying challenges that would be fun to solve, which we’ll explore next.

1.1 Data Dictonary

A lot of the terminology used within this dataset was new to me. I am including here the Data Dictionary for all fields and columns we’ll be using in our analysis for reference. This can be found on https://cneos.jpl.nasa.gov/ca/ and https://cneos.jpl.nasa.gov/sentry/ by expanding Table Column Descriptions.

NEO Earth Close Approaches

  • Object: Designation of NEO (Name)
  • Close-Approach (CA) Date: Date and time (TDB) of closest Earth approach.
  • CA Distance Nominal (LD | au): The most likely (Nominal) close-approach distance (Earth center to NEO center), in LD (Lunar Distance) and au.
  • V relative (km/s): Object velocity relative to Earth at close-approach.
  • Estimated Diameter: Diameter range (min - max) estimated from the asteroid’s absolute magnitude (H) and limiting albedos of 0.25 and 0.05.
  • au: One Astronomical Unit (au) is approximately 150 million kilometers
  • LD: One Lunar Distance (LD) is approximately 384,000 kilometers

Sentry Earth Impact Monitoring

  • Year Range: Time span over which impacts have been detected
  • Potential Impacts: Number of dynamically distinct potential impacts that have been detected by Sentry
  • Impact Probability (cumulative): Sum of the impact probabilities from all detected potential impacts.
  • Palermo Scale (cum.): Cumulative hazard rating according to the Palermo technical impact hazard scale, based on the tabulated impact date, impact probability and impact energy.
  • Palermo Scale (max.): Maximum hazard rating according to the Palermo technical impact hazard scale, based on the tabulated impact date, impact probability and impact energy.
  • Torino Scale (max.): Maximum detected hazard rating according to the Torino impact hazard scale, based on the tabulated impact probability and impact energy. The Torino scale is defined only for potential impacts less than 100 years in the future.

3 Data Prep

3.1 Download the NEO Datasets

The datasets I used were downloaded on 2/18/2020.

NEO Close Approach Data from: https://cneos.jpl.nasa.gov/ca/

Table Filters:

  • All Available Data
  • Nominal Dist. <=0.05au
  • no H limit

Sentry Earth Impact Monitoring from https://cneos.jpl.nasa.gov/sentry/

Table Filters:

  • Observed Anytime
  • Any Impact Probability
  • Any Palermo scale
  • Any H

3.2 Import

Once downloaded, we can place them into a datafiles folder within out working directory and import into R.

cneos_closeapproach_data <- read.csv("datafiles/cneos_closeapproach_data.csv", 
                                     stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
cneos_sentry_summary_data <- read.csv("datafiles/cneos_sentry_summary_data.csv", 
                                      stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

3.3 Clean & Prep

There is a lot of prep to do here, and then possibly some follow-up prep as we go along.

3.3.1 Clean column names

colnames(cneos_closeapproach_data) <- c("Object", "Close-Approach_Date", "CA_Distance_Nominal", 
                                        "CA_Distance_Minimum", "V_Relative", "V_Infinity", "H", "Est._Diameter", "UniqueID")

colnames(cneos_sentry_summary_data) <- c("Object", "Year_Range", "Potential_Impacts", 
                                         "Cum_Impact_Probability", "V_Infinity", "H", "Est._Diameter", 
                                         "Palermo_Scale_cum", "Palermo_Scale_max", "Torino_Scale", "UniqueID")

3.3.2 Format Close Approach Date

cneos_closeapproach_data$`Close-Approach_Date` <-  substring(cneos_closeapproach_data$`Close-Approach_Date`,1,11)

3.3.3 Remove unneeded columns

cneos_closeapproach_data  <- select(cneos_closeapproach_data, 
                                    -V_Infinity, 
                                    -H, 
                                    -CA_Distance_Minimum)
cneos_sentry_summary_data <- select(cneos_sentry_summary_data, 
                                    -Est._Diameter, 
                                    -Object, 
                                    -V_Infinity, 
                                    -H)

3.3.4 Join the data

We can now join the two datasets. We’ll be doing a left outer and an inner join, so that we have the option to explore the entire set of NEOs (though this may not be used too much) as well as a the subsetted one that includes only NEOs with a chance to strike Earth.

collision_NEO <- inner_join(cneos_closeapproach_data, 
                            cneos_sentry_summary_data, 
                            by = "UniqueID")
all_NEO <- left_join(cneos_closeapproach_data, 
                                cneos_sentry_summary_data, 
                                by = "UniqueID")

3.3.5 Fix Object Name

One problem we can see is that the dataset has includes parenthesis around the Object names. I’d like to remove that to make our lives a bit easier. For instance, the first object in the dataset looks like this: (2019 DS1)

collision_NEO$Object <- gsub('[\\(\\)]', '', collision_NEO$Object)

Now, it looks better: 2019 DS1

3.3.6 Create Average Diameter Field

The last initial data prep step I’d like to take before digging in has to do with the Estimated Diameter column, which at the moment looks like this:

knitr::kable(
  collision_NEO$Est._Diameter[1:5],
  caption = "First 5 Rows of Estimated Diameter"
)
First 5 Rows of Estimated Diameter
x
20 m - 45 m
3.8 m - 8.6 m
5.3 m - 12 m
8.0 m - 18 m
5.3 m - 12 m

This format format is pretty useless to us. I’d like to get those min and max values into their own columns, and then also create an average diameter column for each object that we can use.

3.3.6.1 Minimum Diameter Range

We’ll start by isolating the minimum value into its own column.

collision_NEO$diam_min <- str_split_fixed(collision_NEO$Est._Diameter, "-", 2)[1:nrow(collision_NEO)]

The data includes measurements of meters and kilometers. We’ll clean up the the meters first. I run the the first line 3 times because it removes one space at a time, and I wanted to make sure it got all of them. I expect there is a better way to do this, but it got the job done. The second part removes the m from the string.

collision_NEO$diam_min <- str_remove(collision_NEO[collision_NEO$diam_min %like% 'm',]$diam_min, "[ ]") 
collision_NEO$diam_min <- str_remove(collision_NEO[collision_NEO$diam_min %like% 'm',]$diam_min, "[ ]") 
collision_NEO$diam_min <- str_remove(collision_NEO[collision_NEO$diam_min %like% 'm',]$diam_min, "[ ]")
collision_NEO$diam_min <- str_remove(collision_NEO$diam_min, "[m]")

Some of the values were so big they went into kilometer measurements. My solution here is not terribly clean, but there were so few that it worked for this data set.

Step 1: find the k values.

collision_NEO[collision_NEO$diam_min %like% 'k',]$diam_min
## [1] "1.0k" "1.0k" "1.0k" "1.0k" "1.0k" "1.0k" "1.0k" "1.0k"

Next, reassign them into their appropriate meter values, then finish off by making the column numeric.

collision_NEO[collision_NEO$diam_min %like% 'k',]$diam_min <- c("1000","1000","1000","1000","1000","1000","1000","1000")
collision_NEO$diam_min <- as.numeric(collision_NEO$diam_min)

Repeat the entire process for the maximum range.

collision_NEO$diam_max <- str_split_fixed(collision_NEO$Est._Diameter, "-", 2)[1:nrow(collision_NEO),2]
collision_NEO$diam_max <- str_remove(collision_NEO$diam_max, "[ ]") 
collision_NEO$diam_max <- str_remove(collision_NEO$diam_max, "[ ]") 
collision_NEO$diam_max <- str_remove(collision_NEO$diam_max, "[ ]")
collision_NEO$diam_max <- str_remove(collision_NEO$diam_max, "[m]") 
collision_NEO[collision_NEO$diam_max %like% 'k',]$diam_max <- c("2300", "2300", "1100", "1000",
                                                                "2300", "1200", "2300", "2300",
                                                                "2300", "2300", "2300")
collision_NEO$diam_max <- as.numeric(collision_NEO$diam_max)

And finally, we can create a brand new column that has the **average diameter* of each NEO.

collision_NEO$avg_diameter <- (collision_NEO$diam_min + collision_NEO$diam_max)/2
knitr::kable(
  collision_NEO$avg_diameter[1:5],
  caption = "First 5 Rows of New Average Diameter Column"
)
First 5 Rows of New Average Diameter Column
x
32.50
6.20
8.65
13.00
8.65

Goodbye, original column!

collision_NEO <- select(collision_NEO, -Est._Diameter)

3.3.7 Polermo Scale Values

Finally, I’d like to tranlate the Polermo Scale into a new column representing the level of concern.

collision_NEO$pscale[collision_NEO$Palermo_Scale_max < -2 ] <- "No Concern"
collision_NEO$pscale[collision_NEO$Palermo_Scale_max < 1 & collision_NEO$Palermo_Scale_max > -2] <- "Careful Monitoring"
collision_NEO$pscale[collision_NEO$Palermo_Scale_max > 0 ] <- "Some Concern"

4.1 What percentage of know NEOs could strike Earth?

Of all known NEOs, past and future, how many of them are flagged by the Sentry Earth Monitoring System?

all_objects <- data.frame(unique(all_NEO$Object))
all_prob_strike <- data.frame(unique(cneos_sentry_summary_data$UniqueID))

The unduplicated count of all objects is 17853, and the unduplicated count of all objects with a potential to strike earth is 986. That means 5.5228813% of all NEOs in our data have a probability to strike Earth.

4.2 Of those objects that could strike Earth, how many close approaches occur each decade?

Because the data includes 299 years of NEO data, I’m going to look at it by decade.

min(year(ymd(collision_NEO$`Close-Approach_Date`)))
## [1] 1900
max(year(ymd(collision_NEO$`Close-Approach_Date`)))
## [1] 2199
collision_NEO <- collision_NEO %>% mutate(decade = floor(year(ymd(collision_NEO$`Close-Approach_Date`))/10)*10)

Do any decades stand out from the crowd?

ggplot(collision_NEO) + geom_bar(aes(x = decade)) +
  labs(title = "Number of Sentry Monitoring Close Approaches per Decade",
       x = "Decade",
       y = "Nbr. of Close Approaches") +
  theme_minimal()

One might infer that the bell curve here is related to better technology helping to increase the rate of discovery of new NEOs, inflating the numbers closer to the present. Discovery date of objects is out the scope of this analysis, but there is a wonderful graphic showing the rate of discovery of new NEOs on Wikipedia

4.3 2010-2020 NEO Sentry Data

It appears though that the decade 2010-2020 had/has the most close approaches of any other decade past or future. How many unique Objects passed by the Earth in that time? We can see already that there are ~1000 close approaches in that decade, and so another bar chart might be unreadable for this set. A better bet may be to group the subset by number of approaches, and see how that looks.

collision_NEO_2010 <- collision_NEO %>% filter(decade == "2010")

collision_NEO_2010_grp <- collision_NEO_2010 %>% group_by(Object) %>%
  summarise(objects = n_distinct(`Close-Approach_Date`))

ggplot(collision_NEO_2010_grp) + geom_histogram(aes(x = factor(collision_NEO_2010_grp$objects)), stat = "count") +
  labs(title = "NEO Approaches on the Sentry Monitoring System",
       subtitle = "Years 2010-2020",
       x = "Nbr. of Approaches",
       y = "Nbr. Objects") +
  theme_minimal()

Most objects in the last decade, it seems, passed by only once.

4.6 But wait…how big are these things?

Let’s take a look. We’ll start by seeing if a histogram gives us a good idea of the size of these objects. For now, we will still be counting on approaches, which may skew the count totals.

ggplot(collision_NEO, aes(x = collision_NEO$avg_diameter)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "All Sentry NEO Object Diameters",
       x = "Average Diameter",
       y = "Total NEO Approaches")

An enormous outlier is making this histogram difficult to read. We can try limiting the x axix

ggplot(collision_NEO, aes(x = collision_NEO$avg_diameter)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "All Sentry NEO Object Diameters",
       subtitle = "550m or smaller",
       x = "Average Diameter",
       y = "Total NEO Approaches") +

This is better, but still we have outliers sitting more than double in size away from the main bins.

ggplot(collision_NEO, aes(x = collision_NEO$avg_diameter)) +

This is better, and gives a good look at how the objects are very positively skewed. Most, it seems, are (relatively) small.

4.7 Is there any correlation to the size of an object and it’s speed?

ggplot(collision_NEO, aes(x = V_Relative, y = avg_diameter)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Comparing Velocity (km/sec) to Avg. Diameter (m)",
       subtitle = "All Years",
       x = "Velocity (km/sec)",

Right off the bat this feels highly uncorrelated. Let’s run it through the cor() function.

cor(collision_NEO$avg_diameter, collision_NEO$V_Relative)
## [1] 0.130391

This doesn’t feel worth following. But is there a correlation somewhere here we can follow?

future_neo <- collision_NEO[year(ymd(collision_NEO$`Close-Approach_Date`)) > 2019,]

While it’s true that the correlation here is weak, it’s also true that the number of smaller objects vastly outweights the larger ones. Would this correlation be strongly if the numbers weren’t so skewed? We can see that aside from only one point, nearly all objects at, around or above 500m in diameter are inching closer to the the -2 cutoff for Polermo Scale. Of the entire dataset, only 1 crosses that barrier.

ggplot(collision_NEO, aes(x = factor(collision_NEO$pscale), y = collision_NEO$Potential_Impacts)) +

This gives us a nice idea of how concerning a threat is, how many times it may pose a threat, and how big that threat might be: Which, considering only one object is in the Careful Monitorying category of the Palermo Scale, isn’t much at all. Visually, though, this lacks the true representation of how often these approaches have, and will occure. Let’s jitter the points and limit the y axis a touch to get a better idea.

ggplot(collision_NEO, aes(x = factor(collision_NEO$pscale), y = collision_NEO$Potential_Impacts)) +
  geom_point(position = "jitter", size = collision_NEO$avg_diameter/65, alpha = .3, color = "skyblue") +
  geom_point(position = "jitter", data = future_neo, aes(x = factor(future_neo$pscale), y = future_neo$Potential_Impacts), size = future_neo$avg_diameter/65, alpha = .3, colour = "red") +
  labs(title = "Palermo Scale of All Sentry NEOs vs Potential Impacts",
       subtitle = "Red = Future Approach, Blue = Past Approach, Point size relative to avg. Diameter (m).",
       x = "Palermo Scale",
       y = "Potential Impacts") +
  theme_minimal() +
  ylim(-50, 350)

4.8 Lunar Distance

One measurement we haven’t looked at yet is Lunar Distance. 1 LD = the distance between the Earth and the Moon. This information is included in the dataset, but it’s combined with AU (distance between Earth and the Sun), so we’ll need to split it out, similar to what we did with Avg. Diameter, and add them to their own column.

collision_NEO$lunar_distance <- as.numeric(substr(collision_NEO$CA_Distance_Nominal,1,5))

I’d like to do a quick correlation analysis with these numbers now.

all_cor <- cor(collision_NEO[, c("V_Relative", "avg_diameter", "Potential_Impacts", "Palermo_Scale_max", "decade", "lunar_distance")], use = "complete")
print(all_cor)

Lunar Distance appears to have no correlation at all to the other measurements, which surprises me, but there it is.

Let’s get a feel for the distribution of distances.

ggplot(collision_NEO, aes(x = as.numeric(collision_NEO$lunar_distance))) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 35) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(as.numeric(collision_NEO$lunar_distance))),linetype="dashed") +
  annotate("text", x = 55, y = 400, label = paste("Mean Lunar Distance:", mean(collision_NEO$avg_diameter)), color = "black") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "All Sentry NEO Object Lunar Distances",
       x = "Lunar Distance",
       y = "Total NEO Approaches")

This is an interesting distribution. Many more close approaches occure at or below 3 Lunar Distances, and then the number of approaches beyond that stay relatively even. Lunar distance appears to be somewhat uniform, and uncorrelated with any other measaurements.

4.9 Returning to October

So far, the most interesting aspect of this dataset, for me, is the monthly distribution of Near-earth Approaches, as displayed in the earlier box plot, repeated below:

ggplot(collision_NEO_2010_month_count, aes(x = factor(Month), y = n)) +
         geom_boxplot() +
         theme_minimal() +
   labs(title = "All Sentry NEO Close Approaches by Month",
       subtitle = "All Years Boxplot",
       x = "Month",

5 Conclusion

While we were able to scrape together a minor correlaton at the end, the only repeatable pattern to be found was the October spike of NEO Approaches. This could be worthy of a futher reading, thought I theorize (with only this analysis as proof, for now) it must have something about the angle of the Earth at that time of year.

It’s a thrilling dataset to work with, and allows a lot of opportunity for data cleaning and manipulation. As far as visual analytics, I’ve only scratched the surface here. I believe there area a lot of exciting avenues this dataset could lead, depending on which way you look at it.
